An `if` statement checks a condition. If the condition is `true`, it runs the code inside its curly braces `{}`.

```java
if (condition) {
  // Code to run if condition is true
}
```

The `condition` must always boil down to a **boolean** (`true` or `false`).

slides.codeSnippet:
class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    boolean isHungry = true;

    System.out.println("Checking stomach...");

    // The code inside {} ONLY runs because isHungry is true
    if (isHungry) {
      System.out.println("Time to eat pizza! 🍕");
    }

    System.out.println("Moving on.");
  }
}

class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    boolean isHungry = false;

    System.out.println("Checking stomach...");

    // This will be skipped!
    if (isHungry) {
      System.out.println("Time to eat pizza! 🍕");
    }

    System.out.println("Moving on.");
  }
}
